<body>
    <%- include('partials/navbar') %>
    <header>
        <h1>Exploring Kenyan Cuisines</h1>
    </header>
    <article>
        <p>
            Kenyan cuisine is a rich tapestry of flavors influenced by various cultures and traditions across the country. From hearty stews to flavorful meats and vibrant vegetables, Kenyan dishes offer a delightful culinary experience.
        </p>
        <section>
            <h2>Ugali and Sukuma Wiki</h2>
            <p>
                Ugali, a staple food in Kenya, is made from maize flour and water, cooked to a thick consistency. It is often served with Sukuma Wiki, a dish made from collard greens saut√©ed with onions, tomatoes, and spices.
                <a href="https://theculturetrip.com/africa/kenya/articles/11-delicious-foods-you-have-to-eat-in-kenya/">[1]</a>
            </p>
        </section>
        <section>
            <h2>Nyama Choma</h2>
            <p>
                Nyama Choma, meaning "roasted meat" in Swahili, is a popular dish featuring grilled meat, typically goat or beef. It is often accompanied by a side of Kenyan-style salsa known as Kachumbari.
                <a href="https://migrationology.com/kenyan-food-guide/">[2]</a>
            </p>
        </section>
        <section>
            <h2>Pilau</h2>
            <p>
                Pilau is a fragrant rice dish cooked with spices, vegetables, and meat or fish. It is a favorite during festive occasions and celebrations, offering a burst of flavors in every bite.
                <a href="https://afrotourism.com/travelogue/kenyan-cuisine-10-kenyan-foods-should-try/">[3]</a>
            </p>
        </section>
        <section>
            <h2>Mandazi</h2>
            <p>
                Mandazi are deep-fried dough snacks, similar to doughnuts, often flavored with coconut milk and spices. They are enjoyed as a breakfast treat or as a snack with tea or coffee.
                <a href="https://migrationology.com/kenyan-food-guide/">[4]</a>
            </p>
        </section>
        <section>
            <h2>Githeri</h2>
            <p>
                Githeri is a traditional Kenyan dish made from a mix of boiled maize and beans. It is simple yet nutritious, often seasoned with onions, tomatoes, and spices for added flavor.
                <a href="https://theculturetrip.com/africa/kenya/articles/11-delicious-foods-you-have-to-eat-in-kenya/">[5]</a>
            </p>
        </section>
    </article>
